## 1. Purpose

This document defines the recommended typography system for OPRMT™ documentation, PDFs, websites, slides, product assets, diagrams, prompt manuals, and repository-adjacent materials.

The purpose of this guide is to keep OPRMT™ materials professional, readable, consistent, and suitable for a technical framework brand.

---

## 2. Typography Principle

OPRMT™ typography should communicate:

```text
precision
structure
authority
technical clarity
professional documentation
enterprise readiness
```

Typography should be clean, readable, and restrained. Avoid decorative, playful, or novelty fonts in official framework materials.

---

## 3. Recommended Font Families

### 3.1 Primary Sans-Serif

Recommended use:

- Headings
- Website text
- PDF body text
- Slides
- Product materials
- Documentation covers

Recommended fonts:

```text
Inter
Aptos
Source Sans 3
IBM Plex Sans
Helvetica Neue
Arial
```

Preferred hierarchy:

| Priority | Font |
|---:|---|
| 1 | Inter |
| 2 | Aptos |
| 3 | Source Sans 3 |
| 4 | IBM Plex Sans |
| 5 | Helvetica Neue |
| 6 | Arial |

---

### 3.2 Monospace Font

Recommended use:

- Code blocks
- Prompt examples
- YAML
- JSON
- CLI commands
- File trees
- Repository paths
- Variables

Recommended fonts:

```text
JetBrains Mono
IBM Plex Mono
Source Code Pro
SFMono-Regular
Consolas
Courier New
```

Preferred hierarchy:

| Priority | Font |
|---:|---|
| 1 | JetBrains Mono |
| 2 | IBM Plex Mono |
| 3 | Source Code Pro |
| 4 | SFMono-Regular |
| 5 | Consolas |
| 6 | Courier New |

---

### 3.3 Optional Serif Font

Serif fonts may be used sparingly for formal report covers, whitepapers, or executive documents.

Recommended fonts:

```text
Merriweather
Georgia
Libre Baskerville
```

Use serif fonts only when they support formal document tone. Do not use serif fonts for prompt templates, code examples, or technical file documentation.

---

## 4. Standard Typography Stack

Recommended CSS font stack:

```css
font-family: Inter, Aptos, "Source Sans 3", "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif;
```

Recommended monospace stack:

```css
font-family: "JetBrains Mono", "IBM Plex Mono", "Source Code Pro", SFMono-Regular, Consolas, "Courier New", monospace;
```

---

## 5. Heading Hierarchy

Use clear heading hierarchy across Markdown, PDFs, websites, and slides.

| Level | Markdown | Recommended Use |
|---|---|---|
| H1 | `#` | Document title only |
| H2 | `##` | Major sections |
| H3 | `###` | Subsections |
| H4 | `####` | Detailed subpoints |
| H5 | `#####` | Rarely used |
| H6 | `######` | Avoid unless required |

Do not skip heading levels without reason.

---

## 6. Recommended Size System

For web and PDF-derived materials:

| Element | Recommended Size |
|---|---:|
| Cover title | 36–48 px |
| Page title | 30–40 px |
| H1 | 30–36 px |
| H2 | 24–28 px |
| H3 | 20–22 px |
| H4 | 16–18 px |
| Body text | 15–17 px |
| Caption text | 12–14 px |
| Metadata | 11–13 px |
| Code text | 13–15 px |

For GitHub Markdown, use Markdown headings instead of manual font sizing.

---

## 7. Font Weight System

| Use | Recommended Weight |
|---|---:|
| Primary title | 700–800 |
| Section heading | 650–750 |
| Subheading | 600–700 |
| Body text | 400–500 |
| Caption | 400 |
| Metadata | 400–500 |
| Button text | 600–700 |
| Table header | 600–700 |
| Code text | 400–500 |

Avoid excessive bolding. Bold should indicate structure, emphasis, labels, or key terms.

---

## 8. Line Height

Recommended line heights:

| Text Type | Line Height |
|---|---:|
| Headings | 1.15–1.25 |
| Body text | 1.45–1.65 |
| Tables | 1.3–1.5 |
| Captions | 1.3–1.45 |
| Code blocks | 1.4–1.6 |

Long-form documentation should prioritize readability over dense layout.

---

## 9. Markdown Typography Rules

For repository Markdown:

- Use one H1 per file.
- Use H2 for major sections.
- Use H3 for subsections.
- Use tables for structured comparisons.
- Use fenced code blocks for code, file trees, YAML, and prompt templates.
- Use bold text for labels or important terms.
- Avoid excessive italic formatting.
- Avoid decorative HTML unless necessary.
- Avoid emoji in official documentation unless explicitly approved.

---

## 10. Prompt Typography

Prompt templates should be visually scannable.

Recommended structure:

```text
Objective:
{{OBJECTIVE}}

Parameters:
- Audience: {{TARGET_AUDIENCE}}
- Context: {{CONTEXT}}
- Constraints: {{CONSTRAINTS}}

Results:
{{EXPECTED_OUTPUT}}

Method:
1. {{STEP_ONE}}
2. {{STEP_TWO}}
3. {{STEP_THREE}}

Tools:
- {{TOOL_ONE}}
- {{TOOL_TWO}}
```

Use monospace formatting for prompt examples, variables, file paths, and structured input blocks.

---

## 11. Variable Formatting

Use double curly braces for variables:

```text
{{TARGET_AUDIENCE}}
{{OUTPUT_FORMAT}}
{{INDUSTRY}}
{{CONSTRAINTS}}
{{TOOLS_ALLOWED}}
```

Use uppercase snake case for variable names.

Preferred:

```text
{{BUSINESS_IDEA}}
{{TARGET_AUDIENCE}}
{{DELIVERABLE_FORMAT}}
```

Avoid:

```text
{{business idea}}
{{TargetAudience}}
{{thing}}
```

---

## 12. Repository Path Formatting

Use inline code formatting for paths:

```md
`docs/OVERVIEW.md`
`assets/brand/BRAND_COLORS.md`
`.github/workflows/release.yml`
```

Use fenced code blocks for file trees:

```text
docs/
├── INDEX.md
├── OVERVIEW.md
├── GETTING_STARTED.md
├── FAQ.md
└── GLOSSARY.md
```

---

## 13. PDF Typography Guidance

For polished PDFs:

| Element | Recommendation |
|---|---|
| Title | Large, bold, navy or white depending on background |
| Section heading | Navy, bold |
| Body text | Slate or charcoal |
| Callouts | Navy border or gold accent |
| Code blocks | Monospace, light background |
| Tables | Dark header with white text or light professional grid |
| Footer | Small, muted gray |

Avoid:

- Overly decorative fonts
- Low-contrast gray body text
- Excessive all-caps paragraphs
- Dense pages without spacing
- Multiple unrelated font families

---

## 14. Presentation Typography Guidance

For slides:

| Element | Recommendation |
|---|---|
| Title slide headline | 40–52 px |
| Section divider title | 34–44 px |
| Slide title | 28–36 px |
| Body bullets | 18–24 px |
| Caption | 12–16 px |
| Code/prompt example | 14–18 px monospace |

Use fewer words per slide and keep prompts or technical examples in boxed sections.

---

## 15. Website Typography Guidance

Recommended web typography:

```css
body {
  font-family: Inter, Aptos, "Source Sans 3", "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif;
  font-size: 16px;
  line-height: 1.6;
}

code,
pre {
  font-family: "JetBrains Mono", "IBM Plex Mono", "Source Code Pro", SFMono-Regular, Consolas, monospace;
}
```

Use strong heading hierarchy and avoid making all text the same size.

---

## 16. Typography Restrictions

Do not use the following for official OPRMT™ materials:

- Comic Sans
- Papyrus
- Brush Script
- Casual handwritten fonts
- Graffiti-style fonts
- Novelty fonts
- Decorative medieval fonts
- Overly futuristic fonts that reduce readability

Official materials should prioritize clarity over style.

